

Callbacks
=========

In JavaScript, a callback is a function that is passed as an argument to another function and is executed 
after some operation has been completed.
Callbacks are widely used in asynchronous programming to handle operations like file reading, 
network requests, or timers.


function GeolocationCoordinates(name, callback) => {
    console.log('Hi', name)
    callback()
}

//callback function

function callMe(){
    console.log("Good morning!")
}

//passing funciton as an arugment

great("vishnu", callMe)

//Hi vishnu
//Goodmonring!

function fetchData(callback) {
    console.log("Fetching data...");

    // Simulate a network request or time delay using setTimeout
    setTimeout(() => {
        let data = { id: 1, name: "Item 1" };
        callback(data);
    }, 2000);
}

function displayData(data) {
    console.log("Data received: ", data);
}

fetchData(displayData);

